Mosque in Temecula wins approval of Planning Committee 
The construction of a mosque in Temecula was the unanimous commitment of the local Planning Committee after five, often heated public consultation. 
Critics accused the project to promote both the terrorism and traffic congestion. 
But according to the Commission by Wednesday evening, the new religious center meets the local requirements and will be an aesthetic eye-catcher. 
The project "is supported by many good people - by Christians, Jews, Baha'is, and many others," said Hadi Nael, Chairman of the Islamic Centre of Temecula Valley on Thursday morning. 
"As Americans that makes me proud." 
"It shows the justice prevails." 
"There are only a few opponents," he added yet. 
